00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:31.000
the Shell Oil Company brings you the

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:33.000
New York 

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:35.000
Philharmonic YOUNG PEOPLE'S CONCERTS 

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:37.000
under the musical direction of 

00:00:37.000 --> 00:01:02.000
Leonard Bernstein.  

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:16.000
And here is Mr. Bernstein. 

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:19.000
<v BERNSTEIN> My dear young friends: On our last 

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:21.000
program we devoted so much time to 

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:23.000
introducing our new Philharmonic Hall to 

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:26.000
you, and to introducing you to the new 

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:29.000
science of acoustics, that we didn't get 

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:32.000
to talk very much about music. So this time 

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:36.000
we're going to make up for it, and 

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:38.000
concern ourselves with the real meat and potatoes of

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:42.000
music -- the main course: melody. 

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:47.000
Most people, when they think of music; think of melody right away,

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:52.000
to some people it's almost the same thing 

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:53.000
-- melody; music. That's the whole meal. 

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:55.000
And they're right, in a way, 

00:01:55.000 --> 00:01:56.000
SKIPPED
even though there are also such things in music as rhythm and harmony and counterpoint and orchestration; but melody is the main course, 

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:01.000
because what is music anyway but sounds that change and move along in time? 

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:03.000
And that's practically a 

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:06.000
definition of melody, too: different 

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:09.000
notes that move along in time, 

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:13.000
one after the other. Well, if that's true, 
(TO PIANO)

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:15.000
then it's almost impossible to write music that

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:18.000
doesn't have melody in it. I mean, if a 

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:20.000
melody is simply one note coming after 

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:21.000
another, 

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:23.000
how can a composer avoid writing 

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:27.000
melodies all the time? 

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:32.000 
He writes one note,

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:35.000
then he writes another,

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:36.000
and he's already got a tiny two-note melody.

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:38.000
That's a melody -- sort of. 

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:42.000
If he adds a third note 

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:45.000
it begins to sound a little more melodic,

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:49.000
and if he then adds a few more

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:59.000
well, we've got Mendelssohn's Wedding March. 

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:03.000
You see? Simple. Where there's 

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:06.000
music, there has to be melody. You can't 

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:09.000
have one without the other. Then why do

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:11.000
so many people complain about music that 

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:13.000
has no melody? Some people say they don't 

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:16.000
like Bach fugues, because they don't find 

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:19.000
melody in them. And others say the same 

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:21.000
thing about Wagner operas, and others 

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:23.000
about modern music, and others about jazz. 

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:25.000
What do you suppose they mean when they 

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:27.000
say "no melody"? What are they 

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:30.000
talking about? Isn't any string of notes 

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:32.000
a melody? Well, I think the answer is in 

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:34.000
the fact that melody can be a lot of 

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:37.000
different things: it can be a tune, 

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:39.000
or a theme, or a motive, or a long melodic 

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:41.000
line, or a bass line, or an inner voice

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:43.000
 -- all those things: and the minute we 

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:45.000
understand the differences among all 

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:48.000
those kinds of melody, then I think we'll 

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:50.000
be able to understand the whole problem.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:53.000
You see, people usually think of a melody 

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:56.000
as a tune, something you go out 

00:03:56.000 --> 00:03:58.000
whistling, that's easy to remember, that 

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:02.000
"sticks in your mind."   Now a tune 

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:25.000
is usually complete in itself -- that is, it 

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:26.000
seems to have a beginning, middle and 

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:27.000
end, 

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:29.000
and leaves you feeling satisfied -- in 

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:32.000
other words, it's a song, like God Save the Queen, or Gershwin's 

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:35.000
Summertime, or Schubert's Serenade. 

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:38.000
But in 

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:40.000
symphonic music, which is what we're 

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:43.000
mostly concerned with here, tunes aren't 

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:46.000
exactly in order, because 

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:49.000
being complete in themselves, tunes don't cry 

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:51.000
out for further development. And, as you'll 

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:53.000
remember from our former programs, 

00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:56.000
development is the main thing in 

00:04:56.000 --> 00:04:59.000
symphonic music -- the growing and changing of a melodic 

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:05.000
seed into a whole symphonic tree. So that 

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:05.000
seed mustn't be a complete tune, but

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:07.000
rather a melody that leaves something

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:10.000
still to be said, to be developed 

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:16.000
-- what is called a theme.

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:17.000
Well, that's already a disadvantage to those people who are always expecting 

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:21.000
music to have full-blown tunes, 

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:23.000
and so they'll naturally find these incomplete

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:27.000
themes less melodic.  I suppose, 

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:28.000
then, that they should complain about the 

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:30.000
famous opening 4-note theme of 

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:32.000
Beethoven's Fifth Symphony: 

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:35.000
which is hardly melodic at all.  Or about 

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:42.000
this theme from his 7th Symphony:

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:45.000
which is all one note. 

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:48.000
But both of those themes are kinds of 

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:50.000
melodies, you must remember, even though they're not tunes.  

00:05:56.000 --> 00:05:58.000
Of course, there are themes that 

00:05:58.000 --> 00:05:59.999
are much more tuneful than those. Only

00:05:59.999 --> 00:06:02.000
think of Chaikovsky's Sixth Symphony 

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:45.000
Why that's practically a whole 

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:48.000
tune in itself.  Now what is it about that big, 

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:50.000
tuneful theme that makes it so

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:52.000
attractive and beloved -- 

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:54.000
besides the fact that Chaikovsky 

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:57.000
was a melodic genius?  The answer is 

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:00.000
repetition -- either exact repetition, or 

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:02.000
slightly altered repetition, within the 

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:05.000
theme itself. It's that repetition that 

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:07.000
makes the melody stick in your mind; and 

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:09.000
it's the melodies that stick in your 

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:11.000
mind that are likely to please you the 

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:14.000
most. 

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:17.000
For instance, let's just 

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:35.000
see how Chaikovsky went about building

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:37.000
up that lovely theme by 

00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:40.000
simply repeating his ideas in a certain 

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:43.000
arranged order -- what I like to call the 

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:46.000
1-2-3 method. The fascinating thing is that so many 

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:48.000
famous themes are formed by exactly this

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:50.000
method; and so I think you ought to know 

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:52.000
about it. Here's how it works: first,

00:07:52.000 --> 00:08:02.000
there is a short idea, or phrase;

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:06.000
2nd, the same phrase is repeated,

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:17.000
but with some small variation;

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:22.000
and 3rd, the tune 

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:29.000
takes off in a flight  of inspiration. 

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:38.000
It's like a 3-stage rocket, or 

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:41.000
like the count-down in a race:  on your 

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:43.000
mark,  get set, go! 

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:47.000
Or in target practices: ready, aim, fire! 

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:51.000
Or in a movie studio: lights, camera, 

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:52.000
action! 

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:55.000
It's always the same, 1, 2, and 

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:58.000
3! There are so many examples of this

00:08:58.000 --> 00:08:59.000
melodic technique I almost don't know

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:02.000
where to begin,  But take, for 

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:04.000
example, our good old stand-by, Beethovens

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:10.000
Fifth, On your mark;  

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:28.000
get set; go! 

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:32.000
Or, do you know that 

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:35.000
haunting tune in the Cesar Franck 

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:37.000
Symphony? Same thing. First, 

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:42.000
a phrase; 

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:45.000
then repeat with a slight 

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:52.000
change, a rising intensity;  

00:09:52.000 --> 00:10:01.000
then the take-off. 

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:05.000
Or Mozart's 

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:13.000
Haffner Symphony: ready, (ORK) aim,  (ORK) fire!  (ORK)  

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:14.000
SKIPPED
The slow movement of Rimsky-Korsakoff's  Scheherazade,  (ORK) (V.O.)  A phrase:  same phrase, altered:  conclusion.  

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:16.000
And so on. There are millions of them, 

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:19.000
examples of this 1-2-3 design; 

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:22.000
and don't forget that the heart of the 

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:25.000
matter is repetition:  2 is always a 

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:27.000
repeat of 1.  

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:30.000
Now that we know a few of the 

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:32.000
secrets that make music sound melodic, 

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:34.000
let's start looking for some of the 

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:36.000
reasons why people find certain kinds of 

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:40.000
music unmelodic.  We've already discovered 

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:42.000
that what appeals to people most as 

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:45.000
melody is a fully spun-out tune, 

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:47.000
and that when they get instead an 

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:50.000
incomplete tune, or a theme, they begin to 

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:52.000
have trouble.  So you can imagine that 

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:53.000
when they hear music made out of 

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:56.000
melodies that are even shorter than

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:59.000
themes, they have even more trouble. For 

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:00.000
example, to return to that famous 4-note opening of 

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:03.000
Beethoven's Fifth:  

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:05.000
That's so short it's not really even a theme, 

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:09.000
but what is called a motive. Now a motive, 

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:11.000
can be as little as 2 notes, or 3 

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:15.000
or 4, -- a bare melodic seed -- the raw 

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:17.000
material out of which longer 

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:19.000
melodic lines are made. You remember 

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:21.000
I said that certain people find Wagner's 

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:25.000
operas unmelodic? This is why: because 

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:27.000
Wagner usually constructed his huge 

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:29.000
operas out of tiny little 

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:32.000
motives, instead of writing regular tunes 

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:35.000
such as the Italian opera composers used. 

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:37.000
But how wrong they are to say that Wagner 

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:38.000
doesn't write melody! 

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:41.000
He writes nothing but melody, only it's 

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:44.000
made out of motives. Let me 

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:48.000
show you how.  You've all heard the prelude to his 

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:50.000
great opera, Tristan &amp; Isolde, I'm sure. 

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:55.000
It begins with a 4-note motive.  

00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:01.000
Now immediately comes another

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:06.000
motive, also of 4 notes. Now the

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:08.000
exciting thing is the way Wagner puts 

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:10.000
these two motives together:  he  makes the 

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:13.000
second motive begin smack on the end of 

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:16.000
the first one, so that the last note of 

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:18.000
one and the first note of the other are 

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:22.000
joined, locking the two 

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:32.000
motives securely together. Like this: 

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:34.000
Now he adds some marvelous harmony underneath, and 

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:35.000
this is what you get, as the beginning of 

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:43.000
Tristan:

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:46.000
Now that's already much more than a 

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:48.000
motive, or even of two motives -- it has 

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:51.000
become what is called a phrase, just as a 

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:53.000
series of words in a language is called a 

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:56.000
phrase. And Wagner, by using this method 

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:59.000
of joining motives together and making 

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:01.000
phrases out of them, and then sentences 

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:03.000
out of the phrases, and paragraphs 

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:06.000
out of the sentences. Finally turns out a 

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:09.000
whole story, a prelude to Tristan that is 

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:12.000
a miracle of continuous melody that seems to have no 

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:15.000
end, even though there isn't a 

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:18.000
tune anywhere in it! Do you begin to see 

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:20.000
what I mean by understanding melody in a 

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:22.000
different way? If you think you don't 

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:24.000
just listen to a couple of minutes of 

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:26.000
this famous prelude now, and I'm sure 

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:28.000
you'll be surprised to find that you do 

00:13:28.000 --> 00:15:18.000
understand it very well.

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:50.000
Well, that's a, lot of 

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:52.000
melody for a composer who is supposed to 

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:55.000
be unmelodic. We have seen how his melody grows, 

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:58.000
starting with a motive, 

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:00.000
then growing to a phrase, then to sentences. 

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:02.000
SKIPPED
And it's not an unusual method of making melody, at all; I've even done it myself, in a more modest way. How many of you know the music of West Side Story? Well, what I like most about that music is how much of it grows out of a simple motive at the beginning of the score -- do you remember it?  
That's the gang call of The Jets --- you hear them whistling it all through the show to call each other. Well, all it is is 3 notes;   
but by juggling them around,  
and changing their order,  
all kinds of new melodies suddenly come to life.
For instance, in this order
