And the same three notes, put into a jumping jazz rhythm, turn out to be a song named "Cool" 
And there are many other ways in which this 3-note motive was used, but I don't want to take time to plug my own music.  I just want you to see how common it is for melody to grow out of motives; everybody does it, even me.  So you see, little motives are as much a part of melody as anything else. 

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:06.000
But now comes an even more 

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:09.000
serious problem 

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:12.000
-- counterpoint. 

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:20.000
That's what mostly gets in people's way when they are trying to hear a melody. 

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:31.000
They are always complaining about "those dry, difficult Bach Fugues! How can I hear the melody when there is so many things going on at once?""    

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:33.000
SKIPPED
Well, your answer to that is:  "Just  open your ears and listen."   You see, people normally expect a melody to be on top of the music, with an accompaniment underneath, like a Chopin Nocturne. But why does it have to be on top? The melody can be on the bottom, or in the middle as well, as in any Bach fugue; but that doesn't make it any the less melodic. It may be a little harder, to have to look for the melody, instead of having it served to you on a silver platter, but think how much greater the satisfaction is when you find it! Now here's the start of a Bach fugue -- a very short theme, but perfectly melodic. Now it gets developed, as new voices join in the discussion, stating the same theme while other voices go on to other melodic statements at the same time.
You see how the main subject keeps turning up in different voices -- way down in the bass, or up on top, or in the middle? While the other voices go on singing other melodies. 

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:36.000
So it's certainly not an absence of melody, not by a long shot; in fact, 

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:38.000
it's an overabundance of melody; 

00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:39.000
SKIPPED
the whole fugue is one long outpouring of melody, just like the Tristan Prelude; only you have to know how to listen for the melody, and where to find it. So don't let anyone scare you with that terrible word counterpoint. 

00:19:39.000 --> 00:19:43.000
Counterpoint doesn't erase melody; on the contrary, it multiplies it.  

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:44.000
SKIPPED
So it all adds up to what I said in the beginning; melody can be many kinds of things, and you mustn't expect it to be always the same thing -- namely, just a tune. It can be a short theme, or even a shorter motive; or it can appear in company with other themes, as in counterpoint, on top, or at the bottom, or in the middle.  But it's always melody, no matter how involved it gets in symphonic development.  

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:44.000
Now that's a lot of hard stuff we've been 

00:19:44.000 --> 00:19:47.000
discussing so far; and so to make it 

00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:49.000
clearer, we're going 

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:51.000
to play you a whole movement from a 

00:19:51.000 --> 00:19:54.000
Mozart Symphony, the 1st movement of 

00:19:54.000 --> 00:19:58.000
his great G-Minor Symphony, which will 

00:19:58.000 --> 00:19:59.999
illustrate everything we've been talking 

00:19:59.999 --> 00:20:02.000
about. I'm sure you all know the 

00:20:02.000 --> 00:20:05.000
beautiful, famous theme that opens this movement 

00:20:05.000 --> 00:20:07.000
-- a perfect example of the 

00:20:07.000 --> 00:20:09.000
1-2-3 method we learned about 

00:20:09.000 --> 00:20:15.000
before; first, a phrase;  

00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:19.000
second, repeat the same phrase, 

00:20:19.000 --> 00:20:25.000
slightly altered;  
and, third, the 

00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:33.000
take-off.

00:20:33.000 --> 00:20:35.000
Now certainly nobody will quarrel with that 

00:20:35.000 --> 00:20:37.000
as being unmelodic; it has such a 

00:20:37.000 --> 00:20:40.000
beautiful shape, and arch. 

00:20:59.000 --> 00:21:01.000
But in the course of 

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:02.000
the movement, as the theme is being 

00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:04.000
developed, there are 

00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:07.000
places that might be called unmelodic, 

00:21:07.000 --> 00:21:10.000
or less melodic. But you're ready 

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:12.000
now to understand that even those places 

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:15.000
are melodic, as much as the opening theme 

00:21:15.000 --> 00:21:18.000
is -- if you just listen to them correctly. 

00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:22.000
For instance, you'll notice that the very 

00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:26.000
first two notes of the main theme 

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:28.000
form a little motive by 

00:21:28.000 --> 00:21:31.000
themselves, 

00:21:31.000 --> 00:21:32.000
a motive that is used all through the movement.

