00:30:57.000 --> 00:31:01.000
Well, so far we've discussed 

00:31:01.000 --> 00:31:03.000
a few of the reasons why some people 

00:31:03.000 --> 00:31:06.000
find certain music unmelodic -- 

00:31:06.000 --> 00:31:08.000
like melodies going against each other, as they do in 

00:31:08.000 --> 00:31:11.000
counterpoint, or a melody singing away 

00:31:11.000 --> 00:31:13.000
down in the bass, not easily recognized, 

00:31:13.000 --> 00:31:15.000
or buried in the middle of a sandwich; or a melody 

00:31:17.000 --> 00:31:20.000
constructed out of tiny motives.  

00:31:20.000 --> 00:31:23.000
But the really 

00:31:23.000 --> 00:31:24.000
important reason -- and I guess this is 

00:31:24.000 --> 00:31:26.000
what I've been coming to all this 

00:31:26.000 --> 00:31:29.000
time -- is the question of what our ears 

00:31:29.000 --> 00:31:31.000
expect -- in other words, taste. 

00:31:31.000 --> 00:31:34.000
And that, in turn, is based on what our 

00:31:34.000 --> 00:31:36.000
ears are used to hearing.  

00:31:36.000 --> 00:31:38.000
For instance, we've seen today how important 

00:31:38.000 --> 00:31:41.000
repetition is in making a melody easy to 

00:31:41.000 --> 00:31:43.000
latch on to.  

00:31:43.000 --> 00:31:44.000
SKIPPED
We're used to that technique -- it's the technique used by popular songwriters: they drum their phrases into your head. 

00:31:44.000 --> 00:31:46.000
OK -- so what happens when we hear melodies that don't repeat at 

00:31:46.000 --> 00:31:49.000
all, that just weave on and on, always new?  

00:31:49.000 --> 00:31:52.000
Well, it's true that we usually like them 

00:31:52.000 --> 00:31:54.000
less -- at first. But that doesn't mean 

00:31:54.000 --> 00:31:56.000
they're any less melodic; in fact, the 

00:31:56.000 --> 00:31:58.000
farther away you get from that kind of 

00:31:58.000 --> 00:32:01.000
repetition, the 

00:32:01.000 --> 00:32:03.000
harder the melodies get to latch on 

00:32:03.000 --> 00:32:06.000
to, but also the nobler and 

00:32:06.000 --> 00:32:09.000
more beautiful they can become. Some of the 

00:32:09.000 --> 00:32:10.000
really greatest melodies ever written 

00:32:10.000 --> 00:32:13.000
are of this kind, non-repeating long 

00:32:13.000 --> 00:32:15.000
lines; but they're not necessarily the 

00:32:15.000 --> 00:32:17.000
ones people go around whistling in the 

00:32:17.000 --> 00:32:18.000
streets.  

00:32:18.000 --> 00:32:20.000
I remember so well the day my 

00:32:20.000 --> 00:32:22.000
piano teacher brought me a new piece to 

00:32:22.000 --> 00:32:24.000
study, 

00:32:22.000 --> 00:32:24.000
Bach's Italian Concerto, when I was 14 years old; 

00:32:27.000 --> 00:32:30.000
and when I began to read the second movement, 

00:32:30.000 --> 00:32:33.000
with its long, noble, ornamental melody line, 

00:32:33.000 --> 00:32:36.000
I simply couldn't understand it.

00:32:36.000 --> 00:32:37.000
It just seemed to wander around, with no place to 

00:32:37.000 --> 00:33:09.000
go. Do you know it? 

00:32:37.000 --> 00:33:09.000
It goes like this:

00:33:09.000 --> 00:33:13.000
And so it goes weaving on, spinning out that 

00:33:13.000 --> 00:33:15.000
long golden thread, never once repeating 

00:33:15.000 --> 00:33:18.000
itself for almost five minutes. 

00:33:21.000 --> 00:33:24.000
I find that melody one of the glories of all music,

00:33:24.000 --> 00:33:26.000
now today; but I sure didn't think so 

00:33:26.000 --> 00:33:29.000
when I was 14.  

00:33:29.000 --> 00:33:31.000
SKIPPED
Why did it seem to me so wandering and aimless? Because every phrase is new and different, instead of repeating previous phrases; and I was still young enough to think that every melody had to be a tune, 

00:33:31.000 --> 00:33:34.000
because that's what my 

00:33:31.000 --> 00:33:34.000
brief musical experience had taught my 

00:33:37.000 --> 00:33:40.000
ears to expect.  In exactly the same 

00:33:40.000 --> 00:33:42.000
way that our tastes change with growing up, 

00:33:42.000 --> 00:33:45.000
and hearing all kinds of music, 

00:33:45.000 --> 00:33:47.000
so people's tastes change from one 

00:33:47.000 --> 00:33:49.000
period of history to another.

00:33:49.000 --> 00:33:51.000
The melodies people loved in Beethoven's 

00:33:51.000 --> 00:33:54.000
time would have shocked and startled the 

00:33:54.000 --> 00:33:56.000
people of Bach's time, 100 years earlier, 

00:33:56.000 --> 00:33:58.000
and I'm equally sure that some of 

00:33:58.000 --> 00:34:01.000
today's modern music, which people 

00:34:01.000 --> 00:34:04.000
complain about as ugly and unmelodic, will

00:34:04.000 --> 00:34:06.000
be perfectly lovely, charming every-day stuff to 

00:34:06.000 --> 00:34:08.000
the people of tomorrow. Let us 

00:34:08.000 --> 00:34:11.000
play you a perfect example -- another long, 

00:34:11.000 --> 00:34:14.000
non-repeating melodic line by the great 

00:34:14.000 --> 00:34:16.000
Modern German composer Paul Hindemith.  

00:34:16.000 --> 00:34:19.000
Hindemith wrote this melody over 30 

00:34:19.000 --> 00:34:22.000
years ago, in a piece called Concert 

00:34:22.000 --> 00:34:24.000
Music for Strings and Brass; and I 

00:34:24.000 --> 00:34:26.000
suppose there are still people who will call 

00:34:26.000 --> 00:34:30.000
this unmelodic, even after 30 years. But I consider it one of the 

00:34:30.000 --> 00:34:32.000
most moving and beautifully shaped 

00:34:32.000 --> 00:34:35.000
melodies, not only of modern music, but of 

00:34:35.000 --> 00:34:37.000
all music; and I have a feeling that 

00:34:37.000 --> 00:34:39.000
you'll agree with me, after all you've 

00:34:39.000 --> 00:36:55.000
learned about melody today

00:38:42.000 --> 00:38:46.000
Now that is a melodic line, four

00:38:46.000 --> 00:38:49.000

00:38:46.000 --> 00:38:49.000
minutes of beautiful curves, arches, peaks 

00:38:49.000 --> 00:38:52.000
and valleys. 

00:38:52.000 --> 00:38:54.000
And if there are any of you who did not 

00:38:54.000 --> 00:38:58.000
like it, who found it unmelodic, awkward, or 

00:38:58.000 --> 00:39:01.000
graceless, let me comfort you by saying 

00:39:01.000 --> 00:39:04.000
that those were just the words 

00:39:04.000 --> 00:39:06.000
used 80 years ago about another 

00:39:06.000 --> 00:39:10.000
German composer named Brahms.  Now these 

00:39:10.000 --> 00:39:12.000
days, when we think of melody, we almost 

00:39:12.000 --> 00:39:15.000
immediately think of Brahms; but 

00:39:15.000 --> 00:39:17.000
there was a time when people complained 

00:39:17.000 --> 00:39:19.000
bitterly about his music as 

00:39:19.000 --> 00:39:22.000
totally lacking in melody. And so, to wind 

00:39:22.000 --> 00:39:24.000
up our program on melody, 

00:39:24.000 --> 00:39:27.000
and to show you how careful you have to be in 

00:39:27.000 --> 00:39:29.000
judging melody, 

00:39:29.000 --> 00:39:31.000
We are going to 

00:39:31.000 --> 00:39:33.000
play for you the last movement of Brahms 

00:39:33.000 --> 00:39:35.000
4th Symphony -- an extraordinary 

00:39:35.000 --> 00:39:38.000
movement for many reasons, but chiefly 

00:39:38.000 --> 00:39:40.000
for the reason that its main theme isn't a melody at all.

00:39:40.000 --> 00:39:45.000
It's nothing but a scale of six notes 

00:39:45.000 --> 00:39:49.000
plus two notes to finish it off; 

00:39:57.000 --> 00:39:59.000
8 notes  in all, one to 

00:39:59.000 --> 00:40:02.000
a bar,

00:40:10.000 --> 00:40:14.000
And out of those 8 bars comes a series of 

00:40:14.000 --> 00:40:17.000
30 variations, each one exactly 8 

00:40:17.000 --> 00:40:20.000
bars long, and each one containing those 

00:40:20.000 --> 00:40:22.000
same 8 simple notes, always in the 

00:40:22.000 --> 00:40:25.000
same key. 

00:40:25.000 --> 00:40:28.000
That's the whole movement. Now 

00:40:28.000 --> 00:40:29.000
that doesn't sound very promising in 

00:40:29.000 --> 00:40:32.000
terms of melody, does it? 

00:40:32.000 --> 00:40:35.000
And yet, what Brahms gives us in 

00:40:35.000 --> 00:40:38.000
this movement is a work of such glowing, 

00:40:38.000 --> 00:40:41.000
fiery melodic invention as to leave us 

00:40:41.000 --> 00:40:44.000
gasping. How does he do it? 

00:40:44.000 --> 00:40:47.000
By inventing new melodies in 

00:40:47.000 --> 00:40:50.000
counterpoint to that main theme, by a brilliant use of motives -- 

00:40:53.000 --> 00:40:55.000
but I'm sure you'll hear all that without my telling you.

00:40:57.000 --> 00:40:59.000
You're ready now to listen to this 

00:40:59.000 --> 00:41:03.000
so-called unmelodic work of Brahms, and hear it for the magnificent 

00:41:03.000 --> 00:41:06.000
outpouring of melody that it really is. 

00:41:06.000 --> 00:41:09.000
And if you're still wondering what a 

00:41:09.000 --> 00:41:12.000
melody is, just listen to this Brahms movement, and 

00:41:12.000 --> 00:41:15.000
you'11 have the answer: melody is exactly 

00:41:15.000 --> 00:43:35.000
what a great composer wants it to be.

